Biography of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang

Zhang Tingwei Shizhi was from Duyang, and his courtesy name was Ji. He had an elder brother named Zhong with whom he lived together. He became a riding official through his family wealth and served Emperor Xiaowen. For ten years he was not promoted and remained unknown. Shizhi said, "Long-term service has reduced my brother's property, yet I have not succeeded." He wished to resign and return home. Yuan Ang, a commander of the central division, knew of his virtue and regretted his departure, so he requested that Shizhi be transferred to serve as a reception officer. After Shizhi finished his court duties, he took the opportunity to speak on matters of immediate benefit. Emperor Wen said, "Keep it simple; do not make overly high-sounding arguments; let them be things that can be implemented today." Thus Shizhi spoke at length about matters between Qin and Han, explaining why Qin fell and why Han rose. Emperor Wen praised him and appointed Shizhi as the head of the reception officers.

Shizhi accompanied the emperor on a visit to the Tiger Pavilion. The emperor asked the superintendent of the Upper Garden about the registers of birds and beasts, posing more than ten questions. The superintendent glanced around but could not answer any. The keeper of the Tiger Pavilion answered from the side, providing detailed responses to all the emperor's questions about the animals. His aim was to observe whether the official could respond orally with endless wit. Emperor Wen said, "Should officials not be like this? The superintendent is useless!" He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the keeper as the commandant of the Upper Garden. After some time, Shizhi approached and said, "Your Majesty, how would you rate Zhou Bo, the Marquis of Jiang?" The emperor replied, "He is a person of integrity." Shizhi then asked, "How would you rate Zhang Xiang, the Marquis of Dongyang?" The emperor again said, "He is a person of integrity." Shizhi remarked, "The Marshals of Jiang and Dongyang are both called persons of integrity, yet when they speak, they cannot even form words. How could they possibly emulate this keeper, who is talkative, sharp-tongued, and quick-witted? Moreover, during the Qin dynasty, officials were entrusted to scribes and clerks. These officials competed with each other by being hurried, harsh, and overly scrutinizing. Yet the result was merely formalism without genuine compassion. Therefore, their faults were never heard, and they gradually declined until the Second Emperor, when the empire collapsed like a house of cards. Now, Your Majesty, because this keeper is eloquent, you have promoted him beyond his rank. I fear that the people will follow the wind, striving for eloquence without substance. Furthermore, the influence of the ruler on the people is as swift as the shadow follows the object or the echo follows the sound. Therefore, one must be extremely cautious in making appointments." Emperor Wen said, "Well said." He then decided not to appoint the keeper.

The emperor entered his carriage and summoned Shizhi to ride beside him. They moved slowly, and the emperor asked Shizhi about the decline of Qin. Shizhi answered in straightforward terms. Upon arriving at the palace, the emperor appointed Shizhi as the commandant of the imperial carriages.

Shortly afterward, the crown prince and the King of Liang entered the court together in the same carriage and did not dismount at the司马 gate. Shizhi then chased after them and stopped them, forbidding them from entering the palace gate. He subsequently impeached them for disrespect by failing to dismount at the public gate and submitted the case. Lady Bo, the Empress Dowager, heard of this. Emperor Wen removed his cap and apologized, saying, "I failed to teach my sons properly." Lady Bo then sent envoys to convey an imperial decree pardoning the crown prince and the King of Liang, after which they were allowed to enter. From this incident, Emperor Wen regarded Shizhi with admiration and appointed him as a middle-level physician.

Soon after, Shizhi was promoted to commander of the central division. He accompanied the emperor to Bailing, where they stayed facing north near the latrines. At that time, Shen Furen was also present. The emperor pointed to the new road to Xinfeng and said, "This is the road to Handan." He had Shen Furen play the se, while he himself leaned against the se and sang. His mood was melancholy and sorrowful. Turning to his ministers, he exclaimed, "Alas! If we use stone from the Northern Mountains to make a coffin, line it with hemp and cotton, and seal the gaps with lacquer, how could it possibly be moved!" Those around him all said, "Well said." Shizhi stepped forward and said, "If there is anything within that can be desired, even if the coffin is locked within Mount Nan, there will still be a flaw; if there is nothing within that can be desired, even without a stone coffin, why should one be sorrowful?" Emperor Wen praised him. Later, Shizhi was appointed Tingwei.

Shortly afterward, the emperor went out through the central bridge over the Wei River. A man emerged from beneath the bridge, causing the imperial carriage's horses to startle. The emperor then ordered cavalry to capture him and handed him over to the Tingwei. Shizhi investigated the case. The man said, "I am from a county. Hearing the imperial procession approaching, I hid beneath the bridge. After a long time, I thought the procession had passed, so I came out. Seeing the imperial carriage and its escort, I ran away." The Tingwei sentenced him according to Qin law: anyone who violated the imperial procession ban should be fined. Emperor Wen became angry and said, "This man personally startled my horse. Fortunately, my horse is gentle; if it were another horse, surely it would have injured me? Yet the Tingwei sentences him only to a fine!" Shizhi replied, "The law is what the emperor shares with the entire world. If the law is as it is, and we now make it heavier, then the law will not be trusted by the people. Moreover, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered his immediate execution, it would have been fine. But now that the case has been handed to the Tingwei, the Tingwei is the balance of the world. If this balance tilts, then the application of law throughout the world will become inconsistent, and where will the people know how to act? Only Your Majesty can examine this matter." After a long pause, the emperor said, "The Tingwei's judgment is correct."

Later, someone stole a jade ring from before the seated statue of the High Ancestor Temple. When he was caught, Emperor Wen became angry and handed the case to the Tingwei for investigation. Shizhi examined the law and submitted a report stating that stealing objects used in the ancestral temple should result in execution by public display. The emperor flew into a rage, saying, "This person is so wicked as to steal the utensils of the former emperor's temple. I handed him to the Tingwei intending to have him executed by clan, but you have sentenced him according to the law. This is not what I meant when I wished to uphold the ancestral temple." Shizhi removed his cap, bowed his head to the ground, and apologized, saying, "The law is sufficient as it is. Furthermore, although the crimes are equal, they differ according to whether they are rebellious or compliant. Now, if someone steals from the ancestral temple and is executed by clan, suppose there is even a one-in-a-million chance that a foolish commoner takes a handful of earth from the tomb of the Long Emperor. How would Your Majesty punish him?" After a long time, Emperor Wen discussed the matter with the Empress Dowager, and finally allowed the Tingwei's judgment to stand. At that time, the Commander of the Capital, Zhou Yafu, Marquis of Tiao, and Wang Tiankai, Marquis of Shandu, who was the governor of Liang, saw that Shizhi held his opinions with fairness, so they became close friends. From this point on, Zhang Tingwei was highly praised throughout the world.

Afterward, Emperor Wen died, and Emperor Jing ascended the throne. Shizhi was afraid and claimed illness. He wished to resign but feared severe punishment; he wanted to go and apologize but was unsure how it would be received. Following the advice of Wang Sheng, he finally went to apologize, and Emperor Jing did not punish him.

Wang Sheng was a man who was skilled in speaking about the Yellow Emperor and Laozi. He was a recluse. Once he was summoned and stood in the court, where the three dukes and the nine ministers were all assembled. Wang Sheng, an old man, said, "My sandal strap has come undone," and turned to Zhang Tingwei, saying, "Please tie my sandal strap for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone told Wang Sheng, "Why did you publicly humiliate Zhang Tingwei, making him kneel to tie your sandal strap?" Wang Sheng replied, "I am old and lowly, and I judged that in the end it would benefit Zhang Tingwei in no way. Zhang Tingwei is today a famous minister of the world. Therefore, I deliberately humiliated him, making him kneel to tie my sandal strap, in order to enhance his reputation." When the other officials heard this, they regarded Wang Sheng as virtuous and held Zhang Tingwei in higher esteem.

Zhang Tingwei served Emperor Jing for over a year before being appointed as the governor of the Prince of Huainan's state, still bearing the stain of his earlier offense. After a long time, Shizhi died. His son was Zhang Zhi, courtesy name Changgong, who held the office of a physician but was later dismissed. Because he could not accommodate himself to the times, he never again took office.

Feng Tang was originally from Zhao. His father moved to Dai. When the Han dynasty was established, they moved to Anling. Tang became famous for his filial piety and served as the head of the central division's staff, attending Emperor Wen. One day, as the emperor passed by in a carriage, he asked Tang, "Old man, how did you become an official? Where is your home?" Tang answered truthfully. Emperor Wen said, "When I lived in Dai, my supervisor of food, Gao Qu, often spoke to me about the virtue of the Zhao general Li Qi, who fought under Julu. Now, every time I eat, my thoughts are never away from Julu. Do you know about this?" Tang replied, "He is not as good as a general like Lian Po or Li Mu." The emperor asked, "Why?" Tang said, "When my grandfather was in Zhao, he served as a military commander and was friendly with Li Mu. My father formerly served as the governor of Dai and was friendly with the Zhao general Li Qi, so he knew his character." After hearing about the characters of Lian Po and Li Mu, the emperor was greatly pleased and struck his thigh, saying, "Alas! I could only wish that I had Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals. Then, would I not worry about the Xiongnu?" Tang said, "Your Majesty, even if you obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you would not be able to use them." The emperor became angry, rose, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang and reproached him, saying, "Why did you publicly humiliate me? Do you not have a private place to speak?" Tang apologized, saying, "I, a vulgar person, did not know the taboo."

At that time, the Xiongnu had recently launched a large raid into Chaona, killing the prefect of Beidi, Ang. The emperor took the Xiongnu raids seriously and finally asked Tang again, "How do you know that I cannot use Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied, "I have heard that in ancient times, when kings sent generals, they knelt and pushed the axle of the carriage, saying, 'Within the boundary gate, I control matters; beyond the boundary gate, the general controls them.' Military achievements, titles, and rewards were all decided outside, and then reported upon return. This is not empty talk. My grandfather said that when Li Mu served as a general of Zhao guarding the borders, the taxes from the military markets were used entirely to treat and reward the soldiers. Rewards and punishments were decided outside, without interference from the central government. By entrusting him with full authority and holding him accountable only for results, Li Mu was able to fully utilize his intelligence and ability. He selected 1,300 chariots, 13,000 mounted archers, and 100,000 elite soldiers. Therefore, he drove the Chanyu northward, defeated the Donghu, annihilated the Danlin, suppressed the strong Qin to the west, and resisted the states of Han and Wei to the south. At that time, Zhao was almost a hegemon. Later, when Zhao Wang Qian ascended the throne, his mother was a singer. After Wang Qian took the throne, he listened to the slander of Guo Kai and ultimately executed Li Mu, replacing him with Yan Ju. As a result, the army was defeated, the soldiers fled, and Zhao was captured and destroyed by Qin. Now, I privately hear that Wei Shang, the defender of Yunzhong, used all the taxes from the military markets to treat his soldiers. He also used his private funds to raise cattle every five days to feast his guests, military officers, and attendants. Therefore, the Xiongnu stayed far away and did not approach the Yunzhong border. When the enemy once entered, Wei Shang led his chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many of their forces. The soldiers were all sons of common families, raised in the fields and conscripted into the army. How could they know the regulations of military records and ranks? They fought all day, beheading enemies and capturing prisoners, and reported their achievements to the military headquarters. If even one word did not match, the clerks would punish them according to the law. Their rewards were not given, yet the officials strictly enforced the law. In my humble opinion, Your Majesty's laws are too clear, rewards are too light, and punishments are too severe. Furthermore, Defender Wei Shang was punished for reporting six fewer enemy heads than claimed. Your Majesty handed him over to the officials, stripped his title, and sentenced him to labor. From this, it is clear that even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you would not be able to use them. I am truly foolish and have touched upon a taboo. Death is my only punishment!" The emperor was pleased. On that day, he ordered Feng Tang to carry the imperial banner to pardon Wei Shang, restore him to the post of defender of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as the commander of the chariot and cavalry division, in charge of the capital guards and the chariot troops of the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jing ascended the throne and appointed Tang as the governor of Chu, but later dismissed him. When Emperor Wu ascended the throne, he sought virtuous and capable men and recommended Feng Tang. At that time, Tang was over ninety years old and could no longer serve as an official, so his son, Feng Sui, was appointed as a riding official. Sui's courtesy name was Wangsun. He was also an extraordinary man and was friendly with me.

The Grand Historian says: Zhang Ji's words reflect integrity and adherence to the law without bowing to others' wishes; Feng Gong's discussions on generals are truly meaningful! Truly meaningful! The saying goes, "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." The two men whom these two gentlemen praise and commend are worthy of being recorded in the halls of the court. The Book says, "Neither partial nor factional, the Way of the King is vast; neither factional nor partial, the Way of the King is smooth." Zhang Ji and Feng Gong come close to this ideal. [end of text]


